[How to respond]

Reply with a single fenced block â€” nothing else, no narration.

If you need MORE information from the user, ask in one batch via
clarifications (the runtime renders them as ONE modal with one
field per question; no need to inquire one-at-a-time):

```research
{"status":"ok","body":{
  "done": false,
  "clarifications": [
    {"id":"<short-id>","question":"<one short sentence>","kind":"required"},
    {"id":"<short-id>","question":"<another>","kind":"optional","options":["<a>","<b>"]},
    {"id":"<short-id>","question":"Anything else I should know?","kind":"comment"}
  ],
  "memory_summary": "<one-line: what's the current state of scoping>"
}}
```

Once you have enough information, finalise with done=true and
findings + (optional) resolved_user_inputs + (optional)
ac_proposals:

```research
{"status":"ok","body":{
  "done": true,
  "findings": "<one or two paragraphs: what you learned, what the planner needs to know>",
  "resolved_user_inputs": {
    "<key>": "<value>"
  },
  "ac_proposals": [
    {"statement":"<criterion text>","rationale":"<one short sentence>"}
  ],
  "memory_summary": "<one-line summary for plan_context>"
}}
```

Required keys when `done: false`:

- `body.done` â€” boolean (must be `false` on this branch).
- `body.clarifications` â€” array (1..8 entries). Each entry MUST
  carry `question`. Optional: `id` (auto-assigned q1/q2/... when
  absent), `kind` (`required` | `optional` | `comment`, defaults
  to `required`), `options` (array of string choices â€” leave
  empty for free-form text; ignored when `kind=comment`),
  `default` (pre-fill value), `allow_comment` (boolean â€” exposes
  a per-question comment textarea; defaults to true for
  required/optional, ignored for comment).

Required keys when `done: true`:

- `body.done` â€” boolean (must be `true`).
- `body.findings` â€” one short paragraph the planner reads under
  [Plan context]. Tell the planner WHAT YOU LEARNED that they
  couldn't infer from the raw goal text alone.

Optional keys when `done: true`:

- `body.resolved_user_inputs` â€” object of key/value pairs you
  pulled out of the user's answers. Use stable keys the planner
  can lift into workers' `inputs` (`file_path`, `output_format`,
  `scope_window`, etc.).
- `body.ac_proposals` â€” array of `{statement, rationale,
  origin_clarification?}` entries. Proposed acceptance criteria
  the user's answers suggest. The PLANNER decides what becomes
  `mission_acceptance_criteria`; your proposals are input only.
- `body.memory_summary` â€” short line carried into plan_context.

Clarification kinds:

- `required` â€” the user MUST answer (value field non-empty).
- `optional` â€” the user may skip; an unanswered required question
  is a contract violation. Use sparingly.
- `comment` â€” text-only "anything else?" prompt at end of batch.
  Ignores `options` + `allow_comment`. The user types free-form
  text into a single textarea.

Cap: 8 clarifications per batch. If you genuinely need more,
prioritise the highest-impact ones and re-fire a smaller follow-
up batch on the next iteration. Your batches must stay tight
â€” each modal interrupts the user.

Quality checks the user will judge you by:

- Each question is one sentence, scannable in one breath.
- Use options when the user is picking from a small set ("yes /
  no", "html / markdown / pdf") â€” free-form text is for genuine
  open-ended inputs.
- Don't ask questions you can answer from the goal text + your
  read-only tool surface. Discovery comes first; inquire after.
- On done=true, your `findings` paragraph is what the planner
  uses to draft the mission contract â€” make it specific. Vague
  findings produce a vague plan.
